Measurement, Enforcement, and Price Incentives in Agricultural Supply Chains: Experimental Evidence from Ugandan Dairy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Measurement technology could improve agricultural product quality through price incentives,
 through enforcement,
 or both.
 We develop a model nesting both channels and test its predictions in a field experiment providing digital milk analyzers to 120 milk collection centers serving 2,500 farmers in Uganda.
 Added water falls sharply and butterfat rises modestly,
 yet prices remain unchanged.
 An information intervention affects behavior only when paired with enforcement.
 The data consistently point to enforcement---raising the detection probability for substandard supply---rather than quality-differentiated pricing as the operative channel in this cooperative setting.
\end_layout

