\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many agricultural value chains in developing countries,
 quality is unobservable at the point of first sale.
 Milk,
 grain,
 tea,
 and other commodities are aggregated from multiple suppliers before reaching processors,
 and individual lots cannot be traced once pooled.
 When buyers cannot distinguish high- from low-quality supply,
 the classic adverse selection problem arises:
 producers who invest in quality are not rewarded,
 while those who adulterate their output face no penalty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "2b080e07-2197-39e6-8e29-cfa83db9de24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The resulting equilibrium is characterized by low quality,
 widespread adulteration,
 and uniform pricing that reflects the pooled average rather than individual supply 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "swinnen2007globalization,barrett2022agri"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conventional policy response follows a clear logic:
 make quality observable,
 enable quality-differentiated pricing,
 and let price premia incentivize quality investment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shapiro1983premiums,leland1979quacks"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

carrot
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 channel---measurement enables markets for quality---underpins much of the literature on value chain upgrading 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "REARDON2000195,MINTEN20091728,Ponte01022005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 If buyers can verify compositional attributes and pay accordingly,
 producers have incentives to invest in better inputs and practices,
 and intermediaries have incentives to preserve quality during aggregation and transport 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hansman2020vertical,bold2022market"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Empirical evidence from dairy supply chains broadly supports this view:
 quality-differentiated pricing has been shown to improve milk composition in Indonesia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "treurniet2021potency"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Vietnam 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saenger2013contract"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and group-level incentives can sustain quality improvements in Indian dairy cooperatives 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RAO2023708"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yet in many settings,
 the institutional preconditions for quality-differentiated pricing are absent.
 Cooperatives maintain uniform prices to preserve solidarity among members.
 Concentrated processing sectors face little competitive pressure to differentiate on quality.
 Biweekly payment cycles lock in prices for fixed periods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "casaburi2019infrequent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In such environments,
 even when measurement technology makes quality observable,
 the price channel may not operate.
 Does this mean that measurement technology cannot improve quality?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper provides evidence that it can---through a different mechanism.
 Drawing on the economics of enforcement and deterrence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "becker1968crime"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we show that measurement technology improves quality through an 
\emph on
enforcement
\emph default
 channel:
 by raising the probability that substandard supply is detected and rejected.
 Even when prices remain flat and no quality premia emerge,
 the increased credibility of the accept/reject decision at the aggregation point raises the expected cost of delivering adulterated or low-quality milk.
 The
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of detection substitutes for the
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

carrot
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of price premia.
 This mechanism parallels evidence from other contexts where increased monitoring reduces malfeasance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "olken2007monitoring,duflo2012incentives"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and where third-party verification disciplines behavior even without explicit incentive contracts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "duflo2013truth"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study this mechanism in Uganda’s dairy sector,
 where milk collection centers (MCCs) aggregate supply from thousands of smallholder farmers and sell to downstream processors.
 MCCs pay a flat price per liter regardless of compositional quality,
 and their existing testing capacity is limited to crude checks for freshness and gross adulteration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vancampenhout2021leading"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Water addition to milk is endemic.
 We implement a multi-level randomized controlled trial across 120 MCCs and over 2,500 farmers in which we cross-randomize two interventions:
 (T1) digital milk analyzers installed at MCCs that enable precise,
 rapid compositional testing of every delivery;
 and (T2) an information treatment providing farmers with knowledge about compositional quality parameters and practices to improve them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We develop a model that nests both channels.
 A pricing parameter governs whether MCCs translate measurement capability into quality-differentiated payment:
 when it equals zero,
 the model reduces to pure enforcement;
 when positive,
 a price channel also operates.
 The two regimes generate sharply different predictions for prices,
 the magnitude of quality improvement,
 and whether farmer information works independently or only through enforcement.
 Under enforcement alone,
 the model predicts a large reduction in adulteration,
 a modest improvement in compositional quality bounded at the acceptance floor,
 no change in prices,
 and an information treatment that works only when paired with the analyzer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experimental results align closely with these predictions.
 MCCs adopted the analyzers and used them to screen incoming supply:
 testing of incoming and outgoing milk increased massively.
 Objective milk sample data show that added water fell sharply at treated MCCs,
 while butterfat increased modestly---direct evidence that the enforcement mechanism operated.
 Prices remained unchanged at every stage of the chain:
 MCC buying prices,
 MCC selling prices,
 farmer prices,
 and the prevalence of quality premia were all unaffected.
 The farmer-level information treatment had effects only when paired with the analyzer,
 confirming that enforcement and knowledge are complements:
 information about quality is actionable only when there is a credible threat of detection.
 Directly connected farmers responded more strongly than those selling through traders,
 consistent with the model’s prediction that intermediation dilutes individual detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper makes three contributions.
 First,
 we provide a model that nests enforcement and price-incentive channels and use the experimental variation to identify which dominates.
 The existing literature on quality upgrading in agricultural value chains emphasizes the price channel---measurement enables price differentiation,
 which incentivizes quality investment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "treurniet2021potency,saenger2013contract,bold2022market"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We show that measurement can improve quality even when institutional constraints prevent quality-differentiated pricing from emerging.
 This distinction matters for policy:
 the enforcement channel operates within existing institutional structures,
 while the price channel requires complementary institutional changes in cooperative governance,
 competitive procurement,
 and payment systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 the theoretical framework parsimoniously explains the asymmetric pattern of results---large adulteration reduction,
 modest quality improvement,
 no price response---that would appear puzzling under the price channel hypothesis.
 The model clarifies why measurement technology is most effective on the extensive margin (deterring a costless but risky action) and less effective on the intensive margin (motivating costly investment with bounded returns),
 and why the absence of quality premia is not a disappointment but an expected feature of the enforcement-only equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 the study contributes to a growing literature on the role of information and communication technologies in agricultural value chains 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vancampenhout2022icts,jensen2007digital"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While much of this literature focuses on how ICTs facilitate price discovery or market access,
 we show that digital measurement tools can function as enforcement infrastructure---changing behavior through the threat of detection rather than through improved information transmission.
 This mechanism is relevant beyond dairy,
 in any commodity chain where adulteration is prevalent and aggregation points serve as natural enforcement nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the paper is organized as follows.
 Section 2 describes Uganda’s dairy value chain and the institutional context.
 Section 3 frames the competing channels through which measurement technology may affect quality and develops the research hypotheses.
 Section 4 presents the conceptual framework and derives testable predictions.
 Section 5 details the two intervention bundles and Section 6 outlines the experimental design.
 Section 7 discusses the estimation strategy.
 Section 8 describes the sample,
 data collection,
 and randomization.
 Section 9 examines baseline balance,
 and Section 10 documents attrition and compliance.
 Section 11 reports results at the MCC,
 farmer,
 and milk-sample levels,
 and discusses threats to validity and alternative explanations.
 Section 12 concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background:
 Dairy Supply Chains in Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uganda’s dairy subsector has undergone rapid transformation over the past two decades.
 The privatization of the National Dairy Corporation and the enactment of the Dairy Industry Act of 1998 opened the sector to private investment and established the Dairy Development Authority (DDA) as the statutory regulator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vancampenhout2021leading"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These reforms spurred an influx of foreign direct investment,
 particularly in and around Mbarara in southwestern Uganda---the country’s primary milk shed---where a cluster of processing firms now converts raw milk into UHT milk,
 powdered milk,
 and infant formula for domestic and export markets.
 The sector is one of Uganda’s main export earners.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical dairy value chain connects five actors.
 At the upstream end,
 smallholder 
\emph on
 dairy farmers
\emph default
 produce milk and deliver it---either directly or through intermediaries---to 
\emph on
 milk collection centers
\emph default
 (MCCs). 
\emph on
 Transporters
\emph default
 collect milk from farms and deliver it to MCCs for a fee; 
\emph on
 traders
\emph default
 purchase milk from farmers and resell it at MCCs for profit,
 often pooling supply from multiple producers.
 MCCs bulk and chill milk,
 initiating the cold chain,
 and are distributed across rural areas to facilitate access.
 Once chilled, 
\emph on
 large traders
\emph default
 transport milk in tankers to 
\emph on
 processors
\emph default
 concentrated in Mbarara and other towns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three features of this chain are critical to our study.
 First, 
\emph on
 adulteration is endemic
\emph default
.
 The most common form is the addition of water to milk 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rustagi2022measuring"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which increases the volume a farmer can sell while degrading compositional quality.
 Because raw milk is opaque and its compositional attributes---butterfat,
 solids-not-fat (SNF),
 protein---are not visible to the naked eye,
 moderate water addition is difficult to detect without laboratory equipment.
 Adulteration is essentially costless to the farmer but imposes substantial costs downstream:
 it reduces processing yields,
 compromises food safety,
 and degrades the quality of finished products.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, 
\emph on
 pricing is flat
\emph default
.
 Unlike in more developed dairy markets where processors pay per kilogram of milk solids,
 MCCs in Uganda typically pay a uniform price per liter regardless of butterfat,
 SNF,
 or protein content.
 This flat-price regime is sustained by several institutional features.
 Many MCCs are organized as cooperatives whose members resist price differentiation on grounds of solidarity and equity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "winfree2005collective,bonroy2019freeriding"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Prices are set on biweekly cycles that lock in a fixed rate for all deliveries within each period 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "casaburi2019infrequent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 And the processing sector,
 while growing,
 is sufficiently concentrated that individual MCCs face limited competitive pressure to differentiate on quality.
 The result is a pricing structure that provides no financial reward for higher-quality supply and no financial penalty for lower-quality supply---as long as the milk is accepted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, 
\emph on
 MCCs are the natural enforcement node
\emph default
,
 but they currently lack the capacity to screen quality effectively.
 The MCC is the first point in the chain where individual farmer deliveries can be evaluated before being pooled into a collective tank.
 Once milk enters the tank,
 traceability to individual suppliers is lost.
 The MCC therefore occupies a unique gatekeeper position:
 it is the last point at which an accept/reject decision on individual supply can be made.
 Yet most MCCs rely on only two crude diagnostic tests.
 The lactometer test uses a floating hydrometer to measure density as a proxy for water addition,
 but readings are sensitive to temperature and cannot distinguish intentional adulteration from natural variation in composition.
 The alcohol test assesses protein stability as a proxy for freshness---milk that curdles upon contact with ethanol is rejected as sour.
 Neither test provides information on compositional quality.
 The enforcement threshold that MCCs can credibly impose is therefore low:
 only gross adulteration or spoilage is detected,
 while moderate water addition and compositional variation go unscreened.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These three features---prevalent adulteration,
 flat pricing,
 and weak screening at the aggregation point---define the setting into which we introduce measurement technology.
 The question is whether equipping MCCs with precise,
 rapid milk analyzers changes farmer behavior,
 and if so,
 through what channel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Research Questions and Hypotheses
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Problem-Statement-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central research question of this paper is:
 through what channel does measurement technology affect product quality?
 The literature offers two competing hypotheses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two competing channels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
 price channel
\emph default
 is the conventional account.
 When quality becomes observable,
 buyers can condition payments on measured attributes,
 and quality premia emerge.
 These premia reward quality-enhancing investments and penalize low-quality supply,
 aligning incentives throughout the chain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "swinnen2007globalization,REARDON2000195"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under this channel,
 the causal chain runs:
 measurement
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 price differentiation
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 quality improvement.
 The price channel requires not only measurement capacity but also the institutional ability and competitive incentive to implement quality-differentiated payment schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
 enforcement channel
\emph default
 offers an alternative mechanism.
 Even when prices remain flat,
 measurement technology improves the precision of the accept/reject decision at the aggregation point.
 By raising the probability that substandard milk is detected---much as third-party verification constrains self-reported behavior in other settings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kleven2011unwilling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

---the analyzer increases the expected cost of delivering adulterated or low-quality supply.
 Under this channel,
 the causal chain is:
 measurement
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 higher detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 increased rejection risk
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 quality improvement.
 The enforcement channel can operate within existing institutional structures---it requires only that the MCC has both the capacity and the willingness to reject substandard supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two channels generate sharply different predictions.
 If the price channel dominates,
 we should observe quality premia emerging after analyzer installation,
 price increases for higher-quality supply,
 and quality improvement driven primarily by the intensive margin (investments in feed,
 breed,
 and management practices that raise compositional quality).
 If the enforcement channel dominates,
 we should observe no change in prices,
 no emergence of quality premia,
 and quality improvement driven primarily by the extensive margin (cessation of adulteration) with modest intensive-margin responses.
 Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conceptual-Framework-and"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 develops a model that nests both channels and derives testable predictions that distinguish between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experimental design tests four main hypotheses.
 These correspond to the predictions of the enforcement channel but,
 as Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conceptual-Framework-and"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 formalizes,
 the model's two-channel structure generates contrasting predictions that allow the data to reveal which channel dominates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first hypothesis concerns MCC-level uptake and outcomes.
 Installing milk analyzers at MCCs (T1) enables precise,
 rapid screening of incoming supply.
 Under the enforcement channel,
 MCCs should adopt the technology and use it to enforce quality thresholds more effectively.
 This should raise the average quality of aggregated milk,
 primarily through rejection of adulterated supply,
 even without changes in pricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second hypothesis concerns farmer-level responses to midstream enforcement.
 When MCCs acquire the ability to detect adulteration and compositional deficiencies,
 the expected cost of delivering substandard milk rises for supplying farmers.
 Under the enforcement channel,
 farmers should respond primarily on the extensive margin---reducing or eliminating water addition---because the private gain from adulteration is small relative to the revenue lost upon rejection.
 Intensive-margin responses (investing in feed and handling to raise compositional quality) should be modest,
 because the flat-price regime offers no incremental reward for quality above the acceptance threshold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third hypothesis concerns the farmer-level information intervention (T2).
 Farmers in Uganda often associate milk quality with hygiene rather than compositional parameters,
 and may lack knowledge of the feeding practices that affect butterfat and SNF.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Agricultural extension services tend to prioritize food safety over compositional quality.
 As a result,
 farmers are typically trained on sanitary standards but receive little guidance on how feeding practices,
 forage selection,
 or supplementation affect butterfat and SNF.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The information treatment provides this knowledge,
 effectively increasing the productivity of quality effort.
 However,
 under the enforcement model,
 information alone should have limited effects:
 without a credible threat of detection and rejection,
 there is little return to improving quality.
 The information treatment should therefore be most effective when combined with the analyzer (T1
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

T2),
 reflecting a complementarity between enforcement and knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fourth hypothesis concerns the role of intermediation.
 Farmers who sell through traders rather than delivering directly to MCCs face a weaker enforcement link:
 traders pool milk from multiple farmers before delivery,
 diluting the traceability of individual quality to its source.
 The enforcement channel therefore predicts that directly connected farmers should respond more strongly to analyzer installation than trader-connected farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RAO2023708,mitra2018asymmetric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout


\begin_layout Section
Conceptual Framework and Testable Predictions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Conceptual-Framework-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section develops a model of farmer behavior that nests two channels through which measurement technology may improve quality.
 The model introduces a parameter
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 that governs whether MCCs translate measurement capability into quality-differentiated pricing.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 the MCC pays a flat price for all accepted milk and the model reduces to pure enforcement:
 the analyzer operates solely by raising the probability that substandard milk is detected and rejected.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 a price channel also activates:
 the MCC pays a premium for quality above the floor,
 creating a continuous return to quality investment.
 The model abstracts from the multi-component nature of the intervention bundle (Section 5) to focus on two parameters---the detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and the institutional pricing parameter
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

---through which the analyzer operates.
 As discussed in Section 5,
 the ancillary components (app,
 tablet,
 DDA visits) support the functioning of the analyzer but do not independently generate quality signals.
 The two regimes generate sharply different predictions for prices,
 the magnitude of quality improvement,
 and the interaction between enforcement and farmer information,
 allowing the data to reveal which channel dominates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment and Timing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are multiple MCCs indexed by 
\emph on
m
\emph default
,
 and within each MCC catchment,
 multiple farmers indexed by 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 deliver milk to the MCC.
 Each farmer supplies a fixed quantity of raw milk
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 per period,
 determined by herd size and not adjustable in the short run.
 The MCC pays a flat per-unit price
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 for accepted milk.
 Milk that is rejected earns a salvage value
\begin_inset Formula $s\geq0$
\end_inset

,
 with
\begin_inset Formula $s<p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In practice,
 rejected milk can sometimes be sold on the informal market at a steep discount,
 or it may be a total loss.
 The key assumption is that rejection is costly:

\begin_inset Formula $s<p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally,
 the MCC may also pay a quality premium for milk above the floor.
 We model the price received by farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 as:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
p_{i}=p_{0}+\alpha\delta\beta\left(q_{i}-\underline{q}\right)^{+}\label{eq:price-schedule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 captures the MCC's institutional willingness or capacity to implement quality-differentiated pricing,
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the measurement precision (the MCC can only price on quality it can observe),
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

 is the price-quality gradient when the price channel is active,
 and
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{i}-\underline{q}\right)^{+}\equiv\max\left(q_{i}-\underline{q},0\right)$
\end_inset

 ensures that the premium applies only to quality above the floor.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

---the flat-pricing regime---the price reduces to
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 for all accepted milk,
 and the model operates through enforcement alone.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the price channel is active:
 the MCC translates its measurement capability into quality premia.
 Note that the price channel requires 
\emph on
both
\emph default
 measurement precision (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

) and institutional willingness (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A critical feature of the setting is that the MCC applies a minimum quality threshold
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{q}$
\end_inset

:
 milk is accepted if observed quality meets or exceeds this floor,
 and rejected otherwise.
 However,
 the MCC's ability to enforce this threshold depends on the precision of its quality measurement technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Farmer Actions:
 Quality Effort and Adulteration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 makes two choices that jointly determine the quality of delivered milk.
 First,
 the farmer chooses a level of quality effort
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 that reflects investments in feeding,
 hygiene,
 and handling practices.
 Second,
 the farmer chooses an adulteration level
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

,
 representing the amount of water (or other adulterants) added to the milk.
 The quality of delivered milk is:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
q_{i}=\theta_{i}e_{i}-\gamma w_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}\label{eq:quality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 captures how effectively effort translates into compositional quality (e.g.,
 butterfat),

\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 is the rate at which adulteration degrades quality,
 and
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a mean-zero stochastic shock reflecting natural variation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quality effort is costly.
 We model the cost of effort as a convex function:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
c(e_{i})=\frac{k}{2}e_{i}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

.
 Adulteration,
 by contrast,
 is essentially costless to the farmer---adding water requires negligible input cost---but generates a private benefit
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 per unit of adulterant added,
 reflecting the volume gain from stretching the milk supply:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
B(w_{i})=bw_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Detection and the Probability of Rejection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MCC maintains a minimum quality threshold
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{q}$
\end_inset

 and rejects milk that falls below it.
 However,
 the MCC can only enforce this threshold to the extent that it can actually measure quality.
 Without precise equipment,
 low-quality or adulterated milk may go undetected and be accepted.
 We model this as a detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

:
 the probability that the MCC accurately observes whether
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}\geq\underline{q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability that farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 's milk is rejected is:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\rho_{i}(e_{i},w_{i};\delta)=\delta\cdot\Pr\left(q_{i}<\underline{q}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is low (poor measurement technology),
 even milk that truly falls below the threshold is likely accepted because the MCC cannot identify it.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is high (precise analyzer available),
 substandard milk is detected and rejected with high probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a farmer whose true quality exceeds the floor
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\theta_{i}e_{i}-\gamma w_{i}>\underline{q}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the rejection probability is approximately zero regardless of
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We abstract from the noise term
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the discussion below for clarity.
 Formally,
 the rejection probability also depends on the variance of
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 but this does not change the qualitative comparative statics.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For a farmer whose true quality falls below the floor,
 the rejection probability is
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 The key comparative static is:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\rho_{i}}{\partial\delta}\geq0,\quad\text{with strict inequality when }q_{i}<\underline{q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Better measurement technology increases the rejection probability only for farmers currently delivering substandard milk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Farmer Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The farmer's expected payoff from delivering milk includes both the acceptance/rejection lottery and,
 when
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 a quality premium on accepted milk above the floor.
 Using the price schedule from Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:price-schedule"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the payoff can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
V_{i}(e_{i},w_{i})=\left[1-\rho_{i}\right]\left(p_{0}-s\right)y_{i}+sy_{i}+\alpha\delta\beta\mathbb{E}\left[\left(q_{i}-\underline{q}\right)^{+}\right]y_{i}+bw_{i}-\frac{k}{2}e_{i}^{2}\label{eq:payoff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first term is the stake at risk from rejection,
 the second is baseline salvage revenue,
 the third is expected quality premium revenue (zero when
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

),
 the fourth is the private benefit of adulteration,
 and the last is the cost of quality effort.
 Denote the stake at risk as
\begin_inset Formula $L\equiv\left(p_{0}-s\right)y_{i}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The farmer chooses
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 to maximize
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the two margins in turn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Adulteration decision (extensive margin)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal benefit of adding water is the volume gain
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The marginal cost includes both the increase in rejection probability times the stake and,
 when
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the reduction in the quality premium:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial V_{i}}{\partial w_{i}}=b-\gamma\left[\delta f(\underline{q})\cdot L+\alpha\delta\beta y_{i}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first term in brackets is the enforcement cost (rejection risk);
 the second is the price-channel cost (lost quality premium).
 Since adulteration degrades quality at rate
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

,
 and
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is the density of
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 evaluated near the threshold,
 the farmer stops adulterating when detection is sufficiently high:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
w_{i}^{*}(\delta)=\begin{cases}
w^{+}>0 & \text{if }\delta<\hat{\delta}_{w}(\alpha)\equiv\frac{b}{\gamma\left[f(\underline{q})\cdot L+\alpha\beta y_{i}\right]}\\
0 & \text{if }\delta\geq\hat{\delta}_{w}(\alpha)
\end{cases}\label{eq:adulteration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is an extensive-margin response:
 at the critical detection threshold
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\delta}_{w}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

,
 the farmer discontinuously stops adding water.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 the threshold depends only on the enforcement stake;
 when
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the threshold is strictly lower because adulteration also forfeits quality premia.
 In both regimes,
 the private gain from adding water is small relative to the penalties,
 so even a moderate increase in detection probability can eliminate adulteration entirely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quality effort decision (intensive margin)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order condition for quality effort equates the marginal return---from both reduced rejection risk and,
 when
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the increased quality premium---to the marginal cost:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\delta\theta_{i}\left[f(\underline{q})\cdot L+\alpha\beta y_{i}\right]=ke_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

At an interior solution:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
e_{i}^{*}=\frac{\delta\theta_{i}}{k}\left[f(\underline{q})\cdot L+\alpha\beta y_{i}\right]\label{eq:effort}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The enforcement return
\begin_inset Formula $f(\underline{q})\cdot L$
\end_inset

 is now augmented by a price-channel return
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 optimal effort is proportional to
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 but bounded by the density
\begin_inset Formula $f(\underline{q})$
\end_inset

:
 once the farmer's quality comfortably exceeds the floor,
 the marginal rejection-reducing benefit of further effort is negligible,
 so effort plateaus.
 The enforcement channel motivates farmers to clear the floor,
 not to invest heavily in quality above it.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the return to effort continues above the floor because quality earns a price premium.
 Effort is higher for any given
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

,
 and the diminishing-returns feature is weaker because the price-channel return
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta y_{i}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the floor density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Statics:
 Effect of the Milk Analyzer
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Model-predictions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The milk analyzer increases
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 from a low level
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 (traditional testing,
 e.g.,
 lactometer and alcohol tests) to a high level
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}>\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 (precise compositional analysis).
 The comparative statics differ across the two regimes.
 For each prediction below,
 we state what the model implies under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 (enforcement only) and under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 (price channel active),
 and note whether the prediction distinguishes between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 1:
 Reduction in adulteration (not distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:adulteration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 both regimes predict that adulteration falls when
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 increases.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 adulteration drops discontinuously to zero once
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 exceeds
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\delta}_{w}(0)=b/[\gamma f(\underline{q})L]$
\end_inset

.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the threshold is strictly lower---
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\delta}_{w}(\alpha)<\hat{\delta}_{w}(0)$
\end_inset

---because adulteration also forfeits quality premia.
 In both cases,
 the private gain from adding water is small relative to the penalties,
 so moderate improvements in detection deter adulteration for most farmers.
 This prediction does not distinguish between regimes:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial w_{i}^{*}}{\partial\delta}\leq0\quad\text{under both }\alpha=0\text{ and }\alpha>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 2:
 Compositional quality improvement (distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:effort"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 quality effort is increasing in
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 under both regimes,
 but the magnitude differs.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 the return to effort comes only from reducing rejection probability near the floor:
 once quality comfortably exceeds
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{q}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $f(\underline{q})$
\end_inset

 becomes small and effort plateaus.
 The predicted improvement is therefore 
\emph on
modest
\emph default
,
 concentrated among farmers near the threshold.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the additional return
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta y_{i}$
\end_inset

 persists above the floor,
 so effort is 
\emph on
larger
\emph default
 and quality improvement is more substantial:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
e_{i}^{*}(\alpha>0)>e_{i}^{*}(\alpha=0)\quad\text{for all }\delta>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 3:
 Prices (sharply distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:price-schedule"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the price prediction provides the sharpest test between regimes.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 the MCC pays a flat price for all accepted milk,
 and increased measurement precision has no effect on prices:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\alpha=0:\quad\frac{\partial p_{i}}{\partial\delta}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 improved measurement enables quality-differentiated pricing and quality premia emerge:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\alpha>0:\quad\frac{\partial p_{i}}{\partial\delta}=\alpha\beta\left(q_{i}-\underline{q}\right)^{+}>0\quad\text{for }q_{i}>\underline{q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Flat prices after analyzer installation indicate
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx0$
\end_inset

;
 the emergence of quality premia would indicate
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 4:
 Asymmetric responses (distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both regimes predict that adulteration reduction exceeds quality improvement,
 because stopping a costless action is easier than investing in costly effort.
 However,
 the degree of asymmetry differs.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

,
 the asymmetry is large because quality effort is bounded by the floor density:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\alpha=0:\quad\left|\frac{\partial w_{i}^{*}}{\partial\delta}\right|\gg\left|\frac{\partial e_{i}^{*}}{\partial\delta}\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 the asymmetry is smaller because quality effort has a continuous price return above the floor.
 A very large asymmetry---large drop in added water,
 modest increase in fat,
 no change in SNF or protein---favors
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 5:
 MCC uptake and screening (not distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the MCC's perspective,
 the analyzer provides a better signal of incoming quality at low marginal cost per test.
 Under both regimes,
 a more precise signal enables more effective enforcement (and,
 under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

,
 more accurate pricing),
 which raises average quality
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{m}$
\end_inset

 in the aggregated tank.
 MCCs therefore have a strong incentive to adopt and use the analyzer regardless of the pricing regime:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\bar{q}_{m}(\delta_{1})>\bar{q}_{m}(\delta_{0})\quad\text{under both }\alpha=0\text{ and }\alpha>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 6:
 Interaction between enforcement and farmer information (sharply distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The video intervention increases
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 (the productivity of effort in producing quality).
 This prediction provides the key diagnostic between regimes.
 From Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:effort"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the main effect of training on effort is:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial e_{i}^{*}}{\partial\theta_{i}}=\frac{\delta}{k}\left[f(\underline{q})\cdot L+\alpha\beta y_{i}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

:
 training has 
\emph on
no main effect
\emph default
 when
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is low,
 because without enforcement there is no return to effort.
 A significant positive interaction
\begin_inset Formula $T1\times T2$
\end_inset

 should be observed---training works only when paired with the analyzer.
 Under
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

:
 training has a 
\emph on
positive main effect
\emph default
 even without the analyzer,
 because quality effort earns a price premium whenever
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
 The interaction is smaller and incremental rather than the dominant effect.
 In both regimes the cross-partial is positive:
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial^{2}e_{i}^{*}}{\partial\delta\,\partial\theta_{i}}>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The diagnostic is whether the interaction dominates (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx0$
\end_inset

:
 training works only through enforcement) or the main effect dominates (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

:
 training works through price incentives).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prediction 7:
 Intermediation (not distinguishing)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers who sell through traders face a longer and less transparent transaction chain.
 If traders pool milk from multiple farmers before delivery,
 the effective detection probability is lower:
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{T}<\delta_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Under both regimes,
 this implies that directly connected farmers respond more strongly to the analyzer.
 The intermediation prediction does not distinguish between channels:
\begin_inset Formula
\[
\left|\Delta w_{i}^{*}(\delta|\text{direct})\right|>\left|\Delta w_{i}^{*}(\delta|\text{trader})\right|\quad\text{under both }\alpha=0\text{ and }\alpha>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

