\begin_layout Subsection
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model nests both channels through a single parameter
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The empirical pattern maps onto
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx0$
\end_inset

:
 prices remain flat despite improved measurement,
 quality gains are modest and bounded at the acceptance floor,
 and the information treatment affects behavior only when paired with enforcement.
 Together,
 these results indicate that institutional constraints---cooperative pricing norms,
 limited competition among MCCs for suppliers,
 and organizational inertia---prevent the price channel from activating.
 Measurement technology is necessary but not sufficient for quality-differentiated markets;
 translating measurement capability into price incentives requires complementary institutional changes in cooperative governance,
 competitive procurement,
 or processor-imposed quality-price schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enforcement channel alone is sufficient to account for the central empirical findings:
 strong MCC uptake of the analyzers,
 a large decline in added water,
 a modest increase in fat content,
 no change in prices,
 and no emergence of quality premia.
 The model clarifies why:
 in the
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 regime,
 the analyzer raises the expected cost of delivering substandard milk,
 which deters adulteration (cheap to stop) more than it encourages quality investment (expensive to pursue and bounded in its returns under flat pricing).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Innovation Bundles for Addressing Milk Quality Challenges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In response to the challenge of unobservable milk quality in the Ugandan dairy value chain,
 we designed a first socio-technical innovation bundle targeting Milk Collection Centers (MCCs).
 This bundle aims to enhance transparency,
 improve record-keeping,
 and empower both MCC managers and farmers by making milk quality measurable and visible.
 The bundle,
 developed after extensive consultations with stakeholders and implemented together with the DDA,
 consists of three key components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Milk Analyzer:
 A central component of the innovation bundle is the installation of milk analyzers at MCCs.
 These machines assess milk quality based on a set of compositional parameters,
 such as butterfat content and solids-not-fat (SNF).
 Another important parameter is the amount of added water,
 providing a more accurate assessment of what MCC managers usually test using gravity based methods.
 The testing process is non-destructive and takes less than one minute per sample,
 enabling rapid and accurate quality evaluation of each delivery.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Generally milk was tested per (25 or 50 liter) milk can.
 Sometimes,
 if multiple cans of the same farmer were delivered,
 a composite sample of the different cans were tested.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By providing immediate feedback,
 the milk analyzers help ensure that quality standards are met and maintained.
 More information on the milk analyzer can be obtained from the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "manufacturer's website"
target "https://www.essae.com/milk-fat-analyzer-machine.php"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
