\begin_layout Standard
Milk collection centers were provided with Samsung Galaxy Tab A7 Android tablet computers on which the application was pre-installed.
 Each tablet contained a SIM card with a prepaid data bundle to enable cloud-based synchronization of records.
 The application was developed following offline-first design principles,
 ensuring that all core functionalities remained accessible without an active internet connection and that data were uploaded automatically once connectivity was restored.
 Data bundles were topped up by us on a monthly basis throughout the course of the project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Increasing Farmer Awareness of Midstream Testing Capacity:
 To mitigate potential power imbalances that could arise once MCCs adopt milk analyzers and to ensure farmers are equally informed,
 we implemented a farmer-facing information campaign using posters displayed at MCCs.
 Designed by a local artist,
 the posters publicized the new testing capacity and encouraged farmers to request free quality tests for their milk.
 By making this service visible and widely known,
 the campaign aimed to equip farmers with accurate information about their product quality and strengthen trust and cooperation between farmers and MCC managers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together,
 these three components form an integrated strategy to make milk quality observable and actionable,
 improving information flows and enforcement capacity throughout the dairy value chain.
 This bundle constitutes the first treatment arm in the field experiment and is referred to as T1 (or sometimes also as the 
\emph on
analyzer
\emph default
 treatment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We emphasize that while the T1 intervention is a package,
 the milk analyzer is the binding constraint.
 The record-keeping application and tablet serve as complementary infrastructure that enables managers to store and act on analyzer readings---they generate no quality signal on their own.
 Similarly,
 the farmer awareness posters inform farmers that testing occurs,
 but without the analyzer there would be nothing to test with.
 The DDA monitoring visits and calibration support ensure the equipment functions as intended,
 analogous to maintenance of any capital good.
 In other words,
 the supporting components make the analyzer effective but do not constitute independent treatment channels.
 We cannot experimentally isolate the analyzer from its support infrastructure,
 but we note that none of the ancillary components alone would increase detection probability---only the analyzer generates the objective quality measurement that makes credible enforcement possible.
 Our theoretical model therefore focuses on the detection probability parameter
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 as the mechanism through which the package operates,
 while acknowledging that the empirical estimates capture the joint effect of the full bundle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address the mismatch between how farmers and processors perceive milk quality,
 we designed an intervention to improve farmers’ understanding of compositional quality and its role in the dairy value chain.
 The treatment combines targeted information,
 practical guidance,
 and modest material support.
 It consists of three components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Educational Video:
 A short,
 engaging video was developed to explain the concept of compositional milk quality (parameters such as butterfat and protein content) and why it matters for both farmers and processors.
 The video also highlights practical management practices and inputs that farmers can adopt to improve milk quality,
 mostly focusing on feeding strategies.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To determine the content of the video,
 we first identified the top five practices and inputs that are known to raise butter fat and SNF in milk.
 This was done through consultations of experts.
 We found the top 5 practices and inputs were:
 selection of breed and genetic potential,
 selection of grasses for high-quality forage,
 best practice in silage and hay making,
 correct mixing and dosage of feed,
 and feed supplements like Methionine and Lysine.
 As selection of breed and genetic potential is unlikely to change sufficiently fast give the length of our research project,
 we decided to focus on feeding practices.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The video is designed to be accessible and appealing,
 ensuring key messages resonate with the target audience.
 The video was shown to treatment farmers twice:
 once during baseline data collection in December 2022 and once at the time of installation of the milk analyzers in October 2023.
 The use of videos such as the one we use has been found to increase technology adoption in different settings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "spielman2021information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Cartoon Handout:
 To reinforce the information provided in the video,
 we created a handout in the form of a cartoon summary.
 The cartoons provide a visual,
 easy-to-understand recap of the key points from the video,
 serving as a quick reference for farmers after watching the video.
 This format ensures the information remains accessible even to farmers with limited literacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Improved Pasture Seeds:
 To make the knowledge actionable,
 each participating farmer received a free bag of improved pasture seeds (1 kg of 
\emph on
Chloris Gayana
\emph default
,
 also known as Rhodes grass).
 By planting these seeds,
 farmers can enhance the nutritional value of their pastures,
 a critical factor in increasing the compositional quality of milk.
 This practical input complements the educational components,
 enabling farmers to directly apply the recommendations provided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This socio-technical innovation bundle,
 referred to as T2 (or sometimes also as the 
\emph on
video
\emph default
 treatment),
 seeks to narrow perception gaps around milk quality and strengthen farmers’ capacity to supply higher compositional quality on a sustained basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment
