\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/REST_a_00552"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 clustered at the level of randomization (MCC catchment area level) for descriptive purposes.
 However,
 because this is a randomized experiment with a known assignment mechanism,
 our primary inference is based on 
\emph on
 Fisher randomization inference
\emph default
 (RI).
 We construct the permutation distribution of each treatment effect estimate under the sharp null hypothesis of no effect for any unit,
 using 5,000 random reassignments of treatment status that respect the experimental design:
 T1 is permuted across MCCs (maintaining the number treated),
 T2 is permuted across farmers within each MCC.
 The RI p-value is the fraction of permutation test statistics at least as extreme as the observed statistic (two-sided).
 RI p-values are exact and require no distributional assumptions about errors or cluster structure,
 making them particularly appropriate given that most catchment areas contain a single MCC,
 where asymptotic cluster-robust inference is unreliable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address multiple hypothesis testing within outcome families,
 we exploit a natural property of randomization inference.
 For each permutation under the sharp null,
 we compute the test statistic for every outcome in the family simultaneously and count how many cross the conventional significance threshold.
 The omnibus p-value is the fraction of permutations that produce at least as many individually significant results as we observe in the actual data.
 This directly tests whether the observed 
\emph on
 pattern
\emph default
 of results---not any single coefficient---could have arisen by chance under the null of no treatment effect.
 For example,
 if we observe 3 out of 5 milk sample outcomes significant at the 5 percent level,
 the omnibus p-value is the probability of seeing 3 or more significant outcomes under the null.
 This approach eliminates the need for parametric multiple testing corrections (such as Bonferroni or Benjamini-Hochberg),
 as it controls the probability of falsely detecting a pattern of significance at any desired level.
 In addition,
 we combine primary outcomes into an Anderson (2008) summary index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1198/016214508000000841"
literal "false"

\end_inset

;
 the RI p-value on this index provides a complementary omnibus test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sample and Timeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sample size was determined using a series of power simulations,
 details of which can be found in the pre-analysis plan.
 The primary outcome for these calculations was the price of milk,
 modeled at both the MCC and farmer level.
 At the MCC level,
 prices were assumed normally distributed with mean 1000 UGX/liter and standard deviation 50,
 while farmer-level prices were drawn with the MCC mean and a higher variance (SD = 100) to capture greater dispersion at that level.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Processors set fairly stable procurement prices and MCCs adjust tightly around those.
 The nested nature of the sampling and variance parameters imply an intra-cluster correlation of approximately ρ≈0.20.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We assumed the intervention would increase MCC prices by 30 UGX/liter (medium to large effect size),
 translate into a 40 UGX/liter increase for farmers (small to medium effect),
 and that the individual-level information treatment would generate a 25 UGX/liter increase (small effect),
 with a large interaction effect of 50 UGX/liter.
 Power was calculated for the joint test of all hypotheses being true at the 5 percent significance level using 1,000 simulations across varying combinations of clusters (100–130 MCCs) and farmers per cluster (10–40).
 Results showed that with about 125 MCCs and 20 farmers per MCC (total sample of about 2,500 farmers),
 power was just above 0.80 for a joint significance test,
 while power for individual hypotheses was substantially higher,
 ranging from 0.87 to 0.99.
 At the design stage,
 we decided to target 130 MCCs to account for attrition.
 We note that these power calculations were calibrated for a price-channel hypothesis;
 the enforcement model developed in Section 4 predicts null price effects.
 We discuss ex-post power for the outcomes that matter under the enforcement hypothesis in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Falsifiability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field experiment was conducted in four districts of Southwestern Uganda:
 Ntungamo,
 Mbarara,
 Kazo,
 and Kirihura.
 The study began with a comprehensive census of all milk collection centers (MCCs) in the region,
 from which we sampled 130 MCCs.
 Half of these were randomly selected to receive T1,
 while the other half served as the control.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In some cases,
 more than one MCC were in a particular location (eg.
 in a trading center).
 In such cases,
 MCCs were pooled in the same treatment group,
 as a result,
 the number of clusters was slightly lower than the number of MCCs.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


 In each of the 130 MCCs,
 we then randomly selected 20 farmers who deliver milk to the center,
 half of which were taking the milk themselves and the other half using a trader or transported to get the milk to the MCC.
 Of these 20 farmers,
 10 were randomly assigned to the video treatment (T2),
 while the remaining 10 served as the control group,
 with again in each group half directly connected and the other half connected through an intermediary.
\end_layout

