\begin_layout Subsection
Primary outcomes
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Primary-outcomes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
MCC level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We pre-registered six primary outcomes at the level of the MCC.
 The enforcement model developed in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conceptual-Framework-and"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 generates clear predictions for these outcomes:
 MCCs should adopt and use the analyzers to enforce quality thresholds (Prediction 5),
 but prices and quality premia need not change under the flat-price regime (Prediction 3).
 To capture the aggregate effect across these outcomes (and simultaneously consider multiple hypothesis testing concerns),
 we also construct a summary index following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1198/016214508000000841"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our first two outcomes measure the extent to which quality testing becomes embedded in routine operations at the MCC.
 Specifically,
 we record whether MCCs used a milk analyzer to measure butter fat and solid-non-fat content of incoming milk samples in the last 7 days.
 In addition,
 we asked whether MCCs test outgoing milk deliveries destined for buyers.
 This measure is based on more detailed sales transaction data,
 and is true if for any buyer (eg processor,
 other trader,
 etc) butter fat or SNF was tested using a milk analyzer.
 Together,
 these indicators capture MCC uptake of the enforcement technology,
 the necessary precondition for the enforcement channel to operate.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next two outcomes measure prices:
 the average price at which MCCs purchase milk from farmers during the seven days preceding the survey,
 and the average price MCCs received for sales to various buyers during the last transaction in the previous week.
 The model predicts that these prices should remain unchanged under the existing flat-price institutional structure (Prediction 3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 two outcomes directly capture whether price differentiation by quality emerges.
 We ask whether the MCC pays explicit quality premiums to its suppliers,
 and whether downstream buyers pay a premium for higher-quality milk.
 Under the enforcement model,
 which operates through rejection risk at a fixed threshold rather than through quality-differentiated pricing,
 we do not expect these indicators to change.
\end_layout

