 Consistent with Prediction 5,
 MCCs in the treatment group were substantially more likely to test incoming deliveries:
 the probability of testing rose by 53 percentage points relative to a control group mean of 29 percent,
 a large and highly significant increase.
 We also observe a large and significant increase in the probability of testing outgoing deliveries to buyers.
 These results confirm that MCCs adopted the analyzers as enforcement tools,
 raising the detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 for incoming supply---the key parameter shift in the model.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These self-reported outcomes may raise concerns about experimenter bias.
 However,
 as shown in Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Secondary-outcomes-MCC-uptake"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we obtain similar results when using direct enumerator observations of analyzer use.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to prices,
 we find no evidence that the intervention affected transaction terms at MCCs.
 In the control group,
 the average farm-gate price paid to suppliers was about UGX 1,075 per liter,
 and we detect no significant increase in the treatment group.
 Similarly,
 the average price MCCs received from buyers was about UGX 2,200 per liter in the control group,
 with no evidence that the MCC-level treatment raised buyer offers.
 Critically,
 this null result is not a failure of the intervention but rather is precisely what the enforcement model predicts (Prediction 3):
 the analyzer operates through rejection risk at a fixed price,
 not through quality-differentiated pricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition,
 about 20 percent of MCCs in the control group reported paying a quality premium to suppliers,
 and the same share (11 out of 59) reported receiving a premium from buyers.
 The intervention did not increase the likelihood of such premiums being paid.
 This is consistent with Prediction 3:
 under the flat-price institutional regime,
 the enforcement channel raises quality without requiring any change in the price schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of the compliance issues discussed in the previous section,
 we also estimated Local Average Treatment Effects (LATE),
 instrumenting the actual availability of a functioning milk analyzer with the randomized treatment assignment (See Appendix Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-MCC-LATE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The conclusions remain largely unchanged.
 Overall,
 the MCC-level results confirm the first link in the enforcement mechanism:
 the technology was adopted and used for screening (Prediction 5),
 while behavior changed without any accompanying shift in prices (Prediction 3).
 This pattern---testing up,
 prices flat---is the signature of the enforcement channel operating within a flat-price regime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Farmer level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also define four primary outcomes at the farmer level and combine them into an index to assess overall impact of the interventions on farmer-level outcomes.
 The enforcement model predicts modest increases in quality effort (Prediction 2),
 complementarity between the analyzer and the information treatment (Prediction 6),
 no change in prices (Prediction 3),
 and weaker responses among farmers selling through traders (Prediction 7).

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first outcome is a composite in itself,
 and measures production investment and management practices that are expected to improve milk quality.
 We construct an 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1198/016214508000000841"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index from farmer reports on five recommended practices undertaken in the past year:
 (i) over-sowing new fields with improved forage grasses such as 
\emph on
Napier
\emph default
,

\emph on
Brachiaria
\emph default
,
 or 
\emph on
Rhodes
\emph default
 grasses;
 (ii) using legume pastures such as 
\emph on
Centro
\emph default
,

\emph on
Siratro
\emph default
,
 or 
\emph on
Desmodium
\emph default
;
 (iii) adopting controlled or zero grazing during the last dry season;
 (iv) practicing pasture conservation through hay,
 silage,
 or haylage;
 and (v) using feed supplements such as maize bran,
 crop residues (for example banana peelings),
 or mineral licks.
 This index captures the intensive-margin quality effort
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the model:
 costly ongoing investments in feed and management whose returns are bounded by the flat-price regime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second outcome captures whether buyers actively checked milk quality at the point of transaction.
 Here,
 we distinguish between different categories of buyers (eg.
 MCCs,
 processor,
 trader,
 etc.) and ask if milk was tested using a milk analyzer if the farmer sold milk to this particular buyer in the 7 days prior to the survey.
 The indicator is true if milk sold in the last 7 days was tested by at least one buyer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third outcome is the price received for milk sold.
 Specifically,
 we record the average price per liter obtained in the farmer’s most recent sale during the past seven days,
 inclusive of any quality premiums.
 Farmers reported prices by buyer category,
 and we construct a weighted average across categories using transaction volumes as weights.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Reported prices below 600 UGX/liter and above 1,500 UGX/liter are treated as implausible and set to missing.
 These thresholds correspond to roughly half and 1.4 times the control-group mean price,
 respectively,
 and affect fewer than 2 percent of observations.
 Similarly,
 self-reported daily volume quantities exceeding 500 liters are treated as implausible and excluded.
 To verify that our results are not sensitive to these specific cutoffs,
 we conduct a systematic sensitivity analysis varying both price bounds (500--1500,
 600--1200,
 600--1400,
 700--1500,
 and no trimming) and volume caps (300,
 500,
 700,
 1000 liters,
 and no cap).
 Results are stable across all threshold combinations.
 For volume outcomes that are right-skewed,
 we apply the inverse hyperbolic sine (IHS) transformation.
 Results in raw levels and log(x+1) are qualitatively identical.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We also directly ask whether the buyer pays a higher price for higher-quality milk.
 Under the enforcement model,
 neither prices nor quality premia are expected to change (Prediction 3),
 since the enforcement channel operates through rejection risk at a fixed price rather than through quality-differentiated payment.
\end_layout

