,
 we do not find evidence that the MCC-level intervention alone affected farmers’ production investments and management practices.
 The farmer-level information treatment also shows no significant effect in the fully interacted model.
 However,
 the pooled regression suggests a modest positive effect of the farmer-level intervention (significant at the 10 percent level).
 This modest magnitude is consistent with Prediction 2:
 because the return to quality effort comes entirely from reducing the probability of rejection near the threshold---not from earning a price premium---the incentive to invest is bounded,
 and the model predicts only a limited behavioral response on the intensive margin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The significant interaction term in Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-farmer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 indicates that this effect is driven almost entirely by farmers whose MCCs were also equipped with an analyzer.
 This is direct evidence for Prediction 6 (complementarity):
 the information intervention raises the productivity of effort
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 but this only translates into behavioral change when detection is also high,
 because without the threat of rejection there is no return to improving quality.
 Conversely,
 information alone---without enforcement---has limited effect,
 as the model predicts.
 We also find significant heterogeneity with respect to intermediation for the interaction effect,
 consistent with Prediction 7:
 the significant increase in investment and effort is driven by directly connected farmers,
 for whom the individual detection probability is higher than for those selling through traders who pool milk from multiple sources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among pure control farmers,
 approximately 16 percent report that their milk was tested using an analyzer.
 Farmers linked to treatment MCCs report slightly higher testing rates---by roughly 6 to 7 percentage points in both the fully interacted and pooled specifications---although these differences are not statistically distinguishable from zero.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Although these effects are generally small and imprecise,
 they are consistent with qualitative reports from MCC managers who stated that analyzers were typically used only in suspected cases of adulteration rather than on every single delivery.
 Our outcome measure captures self-reported testing across all potential offtakers,
 not just MCCs,
 and therefore may not fully reflect this selective-use pattern.
 Even so,
 selective but credible testing can still shift behavior:
 the possibility of being tested may be sufficient to deter adulteration,
 a mechanism supported by the compositional improvements documented in the sample-based analysis below (Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Milk-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is precisely the detection-probability channel formalized in the model:
 even stochastic testing raises
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 enough to cross the deterrence threshold for many farmers.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The coefficient on the farmer-level information treatment is likewise positive but imprecisely estimated.
 At the same time,
 the fully interacted model indicates heterogeneity by connection type:
 the information treatment reduces the likelihood of being tested among farmers who supply through traders,
 consistent with Prediction 7.
 We detect no statistically significant interaction between the MCC-level and farmer-level interventions for this outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Across all specifications,
 we find no evidence that either intervention affected the prices farmers receive for milk.
 Control farmers report an average price of UGX 1,019 per liter---a level consistent with MCC-level data once accounting for sales to alternative buyers such as traders or direct consumers,
 who typically pay slightly less.
 Prices received by farmers in both treatment arms are statistically indistinguishable from those of control farmers,
 and this holds for the interaction term as well as for pooled,
 fully interacted,
 and instrumented models.
 Similarly,
 the likelihood that a farmer reports receiving an explicit quality premium does not differ across groups.
 These null price results mirror the MCC-level findings and are fully consistent with Prediction 3:
 in a flat-price regime where the enforcement channel operates through rejection risk rather than quality-differentiated payment,
 improved detection raises quality without altering the price schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall composite index of primary farmer outcomes is not statistically significant.
 This is consistent with the model’s prediction that the intensive-margin response (quality effort) is bounded:
 the return to effort under flat-price enforcement is inherently limited compared with the large discrete response on the extensive margin (adulteration),
 which is captured by the objective milk sample data analyzed in the next subsection.
 Nonetheless,
 the pooled specification does provide some suggestive evidence that the MCC-level intervention modestly improves the combined index,
 and a direct comparison between pure control farmers and those exposed to the full bundle of interventions points to a small but positive shift in behavior (See Appendix Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-farmer-pooled"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Interpreting the null pre-registered primary outcomes.

\emph default
 It is important to be transparent that the composite index of pre-registered primary farmer outcomes is not statistically significant.
 This index was designed under a price-channel hypothesis---it combines improved practices,
 buyer quality checks,
 average sales price,
 and quality bonus receipt.
 Under the enforcement model we develop in Section 4,
 two of these four components (price and quality bonus) are predicted to show no effect:
 the model's central prediction is that enforcement operates through rejection risk,
 not price differentiation.
 Including these two outcomes that are null by construction under the enforcement model mechanically dilutes the composite index:
 the Anderson (2008) weighting scheme assigns positive weight to price and bonus,
 and their near-zero treatment effects drag the index toward zero even when the remaining components (improved practices,
 buyer checks) respond positively.
 A version of the index that excludes price and quality bonus---retaining only the two outcomes for which the enforcement model predicts positive effects---is significant.
 We nevertheless report the pre-registered specification exactly as planned,
 consistent with best practice for the use of pre-analysis plans 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "651546"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The objective milk sample data analyzed below---which directly measures the behavior the enforcement model targets (adulteration and compositional quality)---provides the strongest test of the mechanism.
 The null composite index and the significant milk sample results are jointly consistent with the enforcement model:
 detection risk changes behavior on the extensive margin (stopping water addition) more than on the intensive margin (investing in quality practices),
 and it does not change prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Milk samples
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Milk-samples"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective milk sample data provide the most direct test of the enforcement model's central predictions.
 Enumerators conducted supervised testing at both treatment and control MCCs.
 For one full day at each site,
 all incoming milk was analyzed using milk analyzers,
 yielding precise measures of key quality parameters:
 added water,
 butterfat,
 solids-not-fat (SNF),
 protein,
 and density (corrected lactometer reading).
 These variables are also combined into an index of overall quality.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Samples collected during the initial days of fieldwork in Ntungamo district (before December 5,
 2024) and in Kazo and Mbarara districts (before December 4,
 2024) were excluded because a calibration error in the project Lactoscan was identified and corrected on those dates.
 Results are robust to including these observations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The model generates sharp predictions for these data:
 a large reduction in added water (Prediction 1),
 a modest increase in compositional quality (Prediction 2),
 and a pronounced asymmetry between the two margins (Prediction 4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that the compositional quality measures obtained through supervised testing at MCCs are farmer-level outcomes,
 but they need not correspond to the same individuals who appear in the farmer survey.
 The universe of suppliers observed in the testing data reflects the set of farmers who delivered milk on the specific day of supervised measurement,
 which may include new entrants who began supplying after analyzers were introduced,
 as well as exclude farmers who had previously supplied but stopped delivering.
 Conversely,
 the survey sample includes baseline suppliers regardless of whether they continued or ceased deliveries by endline.
 Each data source therefore captures a different margin of adjustment.
 The MCC testing data reveal changes in the composition and quality of actual incoming supply,
 incorporating both behavioral responses and selection effects induced by the technology.
 In terms of the model,
 these data capture the combined effect of deterrence (farmers who stop adulterating) and selection (low-quality suppliers who stop delivering),
 both of which are predicted consequences of raising the detection probability.
 The survey-based outcomes,
 by contrast,
 capture how the intervention affected the behaviors and perceptions of a fixed cohort of farmers.
 Both perspectives are essential for identifying the mechanisms at play.
\end_layout

