\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-milk-quality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports the results obtained from the analysis of supervised testing data.
 The headline finding is a large and significant reduction in added water:
 milk delivered to treated MCCs contains nearly half a percentage point less added water relative to the control mean of 1.63 percent.
 This result provides strong support for Prediction 1---the extensive-margin deterrence effect---and is consistent with evidence that detection threats operate primarily on the extensive margin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bott2020got"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the model,
 even a moderate increase in the detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 can push farmers past the critical threshold
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\delta}_{w}$
\end_inset

 at which adulteration is no longer profitable,
 producing a large discrete reduction in water addition.
 Density (CLR) rises by 0.44 units,
 consistent with lower dilution and greater compositional integrity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alongside this large adulteration reduction,
 we observe a modest increase in butterfat:
 average butterfat content rises from 3.88 percent in control MCCs to approximately 4.00 percent in treated MCCs.
 This is consistent with Prediction 2---the bounded intensive-margin response.
 The return to quality effort under a flat-price regime comes solely from reducing the probability of rejection near the acceptance threshold,
 and once a farmer's expected quality comfortably exceeds that threshold the incentive to invest further is weak.
 SNF shows a similar directional increase,
 but the estimate is not statistically distinguishable from zero with the current sample size.
 Protein---which is a component of SNF---shows no detectable change.
 These biologically determined components depend on breed and long-term feeding practices that are unlikely to respond to a short-run increase in detection probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The composite index combining all five components indicates a significant improvement of 0.21 standard deviations in overall milk quality.
 Crucially,
 this improvement is driven primarily by the large reduction in adulteration rather than by quality enhancement,
 exactly as the model predicts (Prediction 4).
 The pronounced asymmetry between the extensive margin (added water down sharply) and the intensive margin (fat up modestly,
 SNF and protein unchanged) reflects the fundamental cost asymmetry in the model:
 stopping adulteration requires only that the farmer cease an essentially costless action whose benefit is now outweighed by detection risk,
 whereas increasing compositional quality demands costly ongoing investment in feed and management with returns that are bounded by the flat-price regime.
 Moreover,
 because the supervised testing data capture all actual deliveries on the day of measurement,
 the improvement reflects both behavioral change (deterrence among continuing suppliers) and selection (low-quality suppliers who ceased delivering once the detection probability rose).
 Both channels are predicted consequences of raising
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess whether this pattern of results could have arisen by chance under the null of no treatment effect,
 we conduct an omnibus count test using the randomization inference framework.
 Three of the five individual milk sample outcomes are statistically significant at the 5 percent level.
 Under 5,000 permutations of the treatment assignment,
 the probability of observing three or more individually significant outcomes is 0.022.
 This omnibus p-value directly addresses the multiple comparisons concern without requiring parametric corrections:
 the observed pattern of significance across milk quality measures is unlikely to have been generated by chance.
 At the MCC level,
 two of six primary outcomes (incoming and outgoing testing rates) are individually significant;
 the omnibus p-value for observing two or more significant MCC outcomes under the null is 0.039.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The treatment-on-the-treated estimates,
 presented in Appendix Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-milk-quality-LATE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for completeness,
 are generally less precisely estimated than the intention-to-treat (ITT) effects.
 The instrument only shifts the probability that an MCC consistently uses the analyzer,
 and the first stage is mechanically weaker than the underlying ITT assignment.
 As a result,
 the 2SLS estimator inflates sampling variability because it attributes all treatment effects to the subset of MCCs that actually complied with analyzer use.
 Moreover,
 if assignment affects outcomes partly through channels other than actual machine use---such as expectations,
 monitoring incentives,
 or changes in manager behavior---then the instrument captures only a fraction of the relevant variation,
 further reducing precision.
 Together,
 these factors imply wider confidence intervals for the LATE relative to the more precise ITT estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Secondary outcomes
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Secondary-outcomes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
MCC level
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key question in understanding the effects of the MCC-level intervention is whether the treatment actually changed the visibility,
 availability,
 and operational use of the milk analyzers.
 These intermediate outcomes form the core impact pathway through which the intervention could influence milk quality,
 rejection practices,
 and price formation.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Secondary-outcomes-MCC-uptake"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 therefore reports several secondary measures intended to capture the uptake and functioning of the technology as observed by enumerators during the endline visit.
 Because these outcomes rely on direct observation and on-the-spot demonstrations,
 they offer an objective assessment of whether the treatment altered day-to-day practices at MCCs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first outcome captures whether the enumerator observed the project posters publicizing the milk analyzers and encouraging farmers to request their milk to be tested.
 This variable reflects both the visibility of the intervention to suppliers and the extent to which MCCs engaged in basic communication around quality measurement.
 The second outcome indicates whether a milk analyzer was physically observed at the MCC during the visit.
 A related variable distinguishes analyzers distributed through the project from machines obtained through alternative channels,
 thereby providing a direct measure of compliance with treatment assignment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functionality is assessed through an indicator based on the enumerator witnessing a successful real-time demonstration of the machine.
 This corresponds to the manager performing an on-the-spot test and the machine producing a result without technical failure.
 Finally,
 a last outcome variable captures whether the MCC used the digital record-keeping in the form of an application (including but not limited to the one developed as part of the project) or a file on a computer (generally an excel sheet).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results show clear and sizable treatment effects on the visibility and presence of the technology.
 Treated MCCs are significantly more likely to display the poster,
 suggesting that assignment increased the outward communication of quality testing.
 The presence of a milk analyzer increases by roughly 53 percentage points,
 and the increase is even larger when restricting attention to analyzers supplied directly through the project.
 These effects confirm both compliance and the persistence of the physical hardware at the treatment sites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention also increased the likelihood that MCCs used digital tools to record quality and quantity traded.
 This reinforces the idea that the project induced complementary behavioral changes rather than simple adoption of a single physical asset.
 Because digital record-keeping addresses traceability and transparency---capabilities that strengthen the enforcement of quality thresholds at the accept/reject margin---this result helps explain how the enforcement channel operates in practice,
 producing measurable improvements in milk composition and reductions in adulteration even without price differentiation.
\end_layout

