\begin_layout Subsection
Falsifiability and alternative explanations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Falsifiability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A natural concern is whether the enforcement model is falsifiable---that is,
 what pattern of results would be inconsistent with it?
 We identify four such patterns.
 First,
 if added water had not decreased at treated MCCs,
 the model's central prediction (Prediction 1) would be rejected:
 the enforcement channel requires that adulteration falls when detection improves.
 Second,
 if prices had increased significantly at treated MCCs,
 this would favor a price-incentive channel over the enforcement channel,
 since Prediction 3 specifically states that prices should remain flat under the institutional regime we study.
 Third,
 if directly connected farmers and trader-connected farmers had responded identically,
 this would contradict the detection-dilution mechanism (Prediction 7).
 Fourth,
 if the information intervention had worked independently of the analyzer---rather than only in combination---this would undermine the complementarity logic (Prediction 6) and suggest that knowledge alone is sufficient to change behavior without enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\emph on
Power considerations.

\emph default
 Our original power calculations were calibrated to detect a 30 UGX/liter price effect at the MCC level under a price-channel hypothesis.
 Given that the enforcement model predicts null price effects,
 this raises the question of whether the study was adequately powered for the outcomes that matter under the enforcement hypothesis.
 For the milk sample data---where we observe the largest effects---the control-group standard deviation of percent added water is approximately 3.7 percentage points.
 With 92 clusters and over 2,500 milk samples,
 we have adequate power to detect effects of approximately 1 percentage point at conventional significance levels.
 The observed reduction in added water (0.49 percentage points,
 approximately 30 percent of the control mean) is well within the detectable range.
 For farmer-level survey outcomes,
 power is lower for interaction terms in the fully interacted model:
 with 92 clusters and 8 coefficients,
 the effective degrees of freedom are limited,
 and we interpret null interaction effects cautiously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\emph on
Selection versus deterrence.

\emph default
 The milk sample results capture whoever delivered milk on the supervised testing day,
 not the fixed panel from the baseline survey.
 The reduction in added water could therefore reflect either behavioral change (continuing suppliers improving quality) or selection (low-quality suppliers ceasing to deliver).
 Both mechanisms are consistent with the enforcement model---the model predicts that some farmers below the critical threshold
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\delta}_{w}$
\end_inset

 will stop adulterating while others may exit---but the welfare implications differ.
 Our secondary outcomes on farmer switching provide indirect evidence:
 we find no significant difference in the probability that treated farmers remain connected to their MCC,
 suggesting that the quality improvement is not primarily driven by supplier exit.
 However,
 we cannot definitively decompose the effect because the milk sample and survey populations differ.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Compliance and the exclusion restriction.

\emph default
 As documented in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Attrition-and-Compliance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 non-compliance was substantial in both directions:
 14 of 59 control MCCs had a milk analyzer at endline,
 and 14 of 61 treatment MCCs did not have a functioning machine.
 This two-way non-compliance motivates our LATE estimates,
 which instrument actual analyzer availability with random assignment.
 However,
 the standard LATE interpretation requires the exclusion restriction---that random assignment affects outcomes only through the endogenous variable (analyzer use).
 Because the T1 treatment was a bundle (analyzer,
 tablet,
 application,
 posters,
 DDA support visits),
 assignment could plausibly affect outcomes through channels other than analyzer use per se.
 For instance,
 the ongoing DDA visits or the record-keeping infrastructure could independently change MCC behavior.
 We therefore urge caution in interpreting the LATE as the causal effect of analyzer use alone.
 The ITT estimates---which capture the joint effect of the full package as randomly assigned---remain our preferred specification and are not subject to the exclusion restriction concern.
 The LATE estimates are presented for completeness and to provide a sense of magnitude,
 but we acknowledge that they likely overstate the effect of the analyzer in isolation because they attribute the full bundle effect to a single compliance margin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Video treatment contamination.

\emph default
 A second challenge concerns the farmer-level information treatment.
 At endline,
 only 54 percent of farmers assigned to the video treatment recalled having been shown a video,
 suggesting either recall decay or imperfect implementation.
 More concerning,
 more than one in five control-group farmers reported having seen a video about compositional quality,
 indicating potential contamination.
 This contamination could arise from social interactions within villages,
 shared viewing of agricultural extension materials,
 or recall confusion with other media exposure.
 The consequence of such contamination is straightforward:
 ITT estimates for the video treatment are attenuated toward zero because some control farmers received (or believe they received) the treatment.
 This makes the video arm a conservative test of information provision.
 The significant effects we do find on recall and seed usage (Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Secondary-outcomes-farmer-uptake"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) should be interpreted as lower bounds.
 For the interaction between the analyzer and video treatments---where we find the strongest farmer-level effects---contamination in the video arm would similarly attenuate the estimated interaction,
 making our finding of complementarity conservative.
 We note that the main results of the paper concern the MCC-level analyzer treatment and the objective milk sample data,
 neither of which is affected by video contamination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Experimenter demand and Hawthorne effects.

\emph default
 The implementation of T1 involved ongoing engagement with treatment MCCs:
 DDA technicians conducted periodic monitoring visits to ensure equipment functionality,
 and a WhatsApp group was maintained for troubleshooting and coordination.
 Control MCCs did not receive equivalent attention.
 This differential contact raises the possibility that behavioral changes at treatment MCCs partly reflect Hawthorne effects---responses to being monitored---rather than the enforcement mechanism per se.
 Several features of the results help bound this concern.
 First,
 the strongest effects appear in the objective milk sample data,
 which were collected during a single supervised testing day at both treatment and control MCCs using independent Lactoscan devices---the testing protocol was identical at all sites.
 Hawthorne effects would need to operate through the farmers delivering milk,
 who had no contact with the research team during the testing day.
 Second,
 the pattern of results is highly specific:
 the intervention reduced adulteration and increased testing rates but did not affect prices,
 quality premia,
 or most farmer-level outcomes.
 A generic Hawthorne response would be expected to improve all measured outcomes,
 not selectively improve those predicted by the enforcement model.
 Third,
 the interaction between treatments (analyzer
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

video) follows the predicted complementarity pattern,
 which is difficult to generate through demand effects.
 Nevertheless,
 we cannot fully rule out that the additional attention from DDA visits contributed to the treatment effect,
 and we flag this as a limitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Seed confound in the video treatment.

\emph default
 The farmer-level information treatment (T2) included not only the video and cartoon handout but also a 1 kg bag of improved pasture seeds (Rhodes grass).
 Because the seed was distributed together with the video,
 any effects attributed to the information treatment may partly reflect the material input.
 In particular,
 the interaction effect (analyzer
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

video) could capture complementarity between enforcement and seed provision rather than between enforcement and knowledge.
 We note two mitigating factors.
 First,
 only 42 percent of treated farmers reported actually planting the seed,
 likely because of drought conditions during the season---limiting the scope for the seed to drive effects through improved feeding.
 Second,
 the seed treatment alone (without the analyzer) shows no significant effects on milk quality or farmer practices.
 The interaction effect is driven by the combination of enforcement at the MCC and farmer-level engagement,
 but we cannot cleanly separate whether the active ingredient in T2 is knowledge,
 the seed,
 or their combination.
 This is a limitation of the multi-component treatment design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Project devices at control MCCs.

\emph default
 Five of the 14 milk analyzers found at control MCCs were devices originally distributed through the project.
 These machines were likely moved or sold by treatment MCCs,
 which represents a leakage of the physical treatment to the control group.
 This contamination attenuates the ITT estimate because some control MCCs gained access to the technology.
 The remaining 9 analyzers at control MCCs were acquired independently,
 reflecting autonomous adoption that would have occurred absent the intervention.
 Both forms of analyzer presence in the control group work against finding treatment effects,
 making our ITT estimates conservative.
 In the LATE specification,
 these control MCCs with analyzers are appropriately reclassified as compliers,
 and the instrument remains valid provided that assignment affects outcomes only through analyzer use (subject to the exclusion restriction caveat discussed above).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study provides experimental evidence that measurement technology can improve agricultural product quality through an enforcement channel---raising the probability that low-quality supply is detected and rejected---rather than through price incentives.
 In a field experiment spanning 120 milk collection centers and over 2,500 dairy farmers in southwestern Uganda,
 we introduced digital milk analyzers that sharply increased the precision with which MCCs could evaluate incoming milk.
 We developed a simple model in which a single parameter shift---the detection probability
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

---generates predictions for both extensive-margin (adulteration) and intensive-margin (quality effort) responses,
 along with a clear prediction that prices should not change under the prevailing flat-price institutional regime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical results align closely with the model’s predictions.
 MCCs adopted the analyzers and used them to screen incoming supply (Prediction 5),
 confirming the necessary precondition for the enforcement channel to operate.
 The most striking finding comes from objective milk sample data:
 added water fell sharply at treated MCCs (Prediction 1),
 while butterfat increased modestly (Prediction 2).
 The pronounced asymmetry between these two margins (Prediction 4) reflects the fundamental cost asymmetry in the model---stopping adulteration requires only that a farmer cease an essentially costless action whose benefit is now outweighed by detection risk,
 whereas increasing compositional quality demands costly ongoing investment with returns bounded by the flat-price regime.
 Self-reported farmer survey data corroborate these patterns:
 quality effort increased modestly,
 and only when the information treatment was combined with the analyzer (Prediction 6),
 confirming that enforcement and information are complements.
 Directly connected farmers responded more strongly than those selling through traders (Prediction 7),
 consistent with the model’s prediction that intermediation dilutes individual detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Critically,
 the intervention did not affect prices at any stage of the chain---neither MCC buying prices,
 MCC selling prices,
 farmer prices,
 nor the likelihood of quality premia being paid.
 Under the enforcement model,
 this is not a failure but the expected outcome (Prediction 3).
 The enforcement channel operates through rejection risk at a fixed price and threshold,
 not through quality-differentiated payment.
 Quality improved because the threat of rejection became credible,
 not because superior quality was rewarded with a higher price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The absence of quality premia also reflects deeper institutional features of this market.
 In many dairy cooperatives,
 including those operating in our study area,
 farmers are paid a uniform price per liter regardless of compositional quality.
 These uniform-price policies are defended as preserving solidarity and minimizing conflict among members,
 but they also remove the possibility of transmitting individual-level incentives for quality upgrading.
 In principle,
 cooperatives could respond to downstream quality premia at the collective level,
 even without differentiating prices internally,
 provided they establish credible mechanisms for managing the common-pool quality problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "winfree2005collective,bonroy2019freeriding"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In practice,
 the combination of cooperative governance norms,
 biweekly price-setting cycles that lock in prices for 14-day periods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "casaburi2019infrequent,swinnen2010marketpower"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and a concentrated processing sector with limited competitive pressure to differentiate on quality jointly sustain the flat-price equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central contribution of this paper is to show that enforcement through detection can substitute for price incentives in driving quality upgrading.
 The conventional view holds that measurement technology improves quality by enabling price differentiation:
 once quality becomes observable,
 markets for quality emerge,
 and price premia reward superior supply.
 Our results demonstrate an alternative mechanism.
 Even when institutional constraints prevent quality premia from emerging,
 measurement technology can still improve quality by making the accept/reject decision at the aggregation point more precise.
 The technology shifts the enforcement frontier,
 not the price frontier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This finding has implications beyond the Ugandan dairy sector.
 Many agricultural value chains in developing countries share the same basic structure:
 quality is difficult to observe at the point of aggregation,
 institutional constraints prevent quality-differentiated pricing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hansman2020vertical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and adulteration is a persistent problem.
 In tea,
 coffee,
 grain,
 and oilseed supply chains,
 aggregators face similar challenges in verifying the quality of individual lots within pooled shipments.
 Our results suggest that deploying low-cost measurement technology at the aggregation point can improve quality through the enforcement channel alone,
 without requiring the more demanding institutional changes needed to implement quality-based payment schemes.
 The enforcement channel operates through a simple mechanism---raising the detection probability makes adulteration unprofitable---that can function within existing institutional structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That said,
 the enforcement channel has inherent limitations.
 It is most powerful on the extensive margin,
 where the response is discrete (stop adulterating or not),
 and less effective on the intensive margin,
 where costly ongoing investment in feed and management is required.
 Our results confirm this:
 the large reduction in adulteration is accompanied by only modest gains in compositional quality.
 A transition from enforcement-based quality assurance to price-based quality incentives would likely unlock further quality improvements on the intensive margin,
 but requires institutional changes---in cooperative governance,
 in processor pricing practices,
 and in market competition---that go beyond the provision of measurement technology.
 There are encouraging signs:
 a new large processor specializing in infant formula production has recently entered the market and begun approaching MCCs about supplying under a quality-based payment scheme.
 Increased competition of this kind,
 combined with broader deployment of testing capacity,
 may eventually create the conditions for a transition from flat-price enforcement to quality-differentiated pricing.
\end_layout

